{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dc530c9e-0117-4d90-80ed-9e182ff04f95","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class span support** with implicit conversions from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes overload resolution:\n\n| | Resolves to |\n|---|---|\n| **C# 13 (.NET 9)** | `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` |\n| **C# 14 (.NET 10)** | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` |\n\nThe `MemoryExtensions` overload wins because `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a more specific conversion than `T[]` → `IEnumerable<T>`. But `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — expression trees cannot represent ref struct operations, so the expression tree interpreter throws at runtime.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate by forcing resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`. Either option works:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n\n// Option 2: Cast away the array type so the span conversion isn't applicable\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth prevent the compiler from choosing the `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overload, keeping the expression tree representable and interpretable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"613c8b4c-1251-440c-aad6-3500d045d8a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), which changes how extension methods are resolved. But more relevantly, there's a change related to how `Enumerable.Contains()` is resolved f