pile time, but the runtime interpreter can't handle it—or perhaps .NET 10 changed how `Enumerable.Contains` works in a way that breaks the interpreter. But the span overload resolution change seems most likely. I should think about how C# 14's first-class span types might be affecting method resolution here.\n\nThe fix would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the right overload. Let me verify this against what I know about how the method resolution changed between .NET versions.\n\nIn C# 14, first-class span support means implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are now considered during extension method resolution, making `MemoryExtensions.Contains` a candidate that might be preferred over the `IEnumerable<T>` version. The problem is that expression trees can't represent ref structs like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so the compiler can't encode a call to that method. The user reports a runtime error rather than a compile-time one, which suggests the compiler might be attempting to build the expression tree anyway.\n\nLooking at the lambda assigned to `Expression<>`, the compiler should convert it to an expression tree at compile time. If it resolved `.Contains()` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, that should fail at compile time since expression trees can't handle ref struct operations. But maybe C# 14 changed how method resolution works in expression tree contexts, or there's a subtle behavioral shift happening.\n\nActually, the most likely explanation is that the code was compiled with an earlier version where `Enumerable.Contains` was still being used, and now with C# 14's improved span support, the method resolution has shifted to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead—which expression trees fundamentally can't represent because of the `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter. The real issue is that C# 14's implicit span conversions are changing how `array.Contains(x)` resolves—it's now binding to the `MemoryExtensions`